{"title_page": "Sidi Brahim Riahi", "text_new": "<br />{{Infobox person\n| name               = Brahim Riahi\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a\n| birth_name         = Abou Ishak Ibrahim Ben Abdelkader Riahi\n| birth_date         = 1766\n| birth_place        = [[Testour]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date         = August 7, 1850\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Tunisian\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Ibrahim Riahi,''' his birth name  '''Abou Ishak Ibrahim Ben Abdelkader Riahi'''  (1766  [[Testour]] \u2013 August 7, 1850)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.bnf.fr/fr/14651143/ibrahim_ibn__abd_al-qadir_al-_riyah_i/|title=Ibr\u0101h\u012bm ibn \u02bfAbd al-Q\u0101dir al- Riy\u0101\u1e25\u012b (1767-1850)|website=data.bnf.fr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>, was a [[Tunisia|Tunisian]] ambassador, theologian and  saint. A Sunni Muslim scholar, he is also a poet. He is the grandfather of [[Ali Riahi]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nIbrahim Riahi learned about the group of academics and lawyers from Tunisia, in particular: Hamza Al-Jibas, Saleh Al-Kawash, Muhammad Al-Fassi, Omar Bin Qassem Al-Mahjoub, Hassan Al-Sharif, Ahmed Bou Khurais, Ismail Al -Tamimi, Al-Taher Ben Massoud, and others.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a|date=2020-01-27|url=https://ar.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A5%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%8A%D9%85_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD%D9%8A&oldid=43176304|work=\u0648\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0628\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nSidi Brahim frequented from a young age a kouttab in [[Testour]] and showed talent for religious sciences and learning the [[Quran]]. Upon his arrival in [[Tunis]], around 1782, he studied at the Haouanet Achour madrassah and then at the Bir Lahjar madrassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080302042056/http://www.tunisia.strabon.org/amvppc/Tunis/Dossier%20Patrimoine/10zaouia_fr.html|title=Tourba et Zaouiya: Le mythe ...|date=2008-03-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAround 1790, he began teaching at Zitouna University where the future ministers Ibn Abi Dhiaf and B\u00e9ji Messaoudi as well as the greatest theologians of the time such as Mohamed Bayram IV and Mahmoud Kabadou were among his students.\n\nIn 1801, he was part of an embassy in [[Morocco]], where he stayed for several months, there he discovered the Sufi tariqa of the Tijaniyya and introduced it to Tunisia on his return.<ref>{{Citation|title=Sidi Brahim Riahi|date=2020-01-23|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Sidi_Brahim_Riahi&oldid=166662511|work=Wikip\u00e9dia|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum ==\nSidi Brahim is buried with some of his sons, sheikhs and theologians like him, in his mausoleum in the  Sidi Brahim Riahi street in the medina of Tunis named [[Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum]].\n[[File:Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum - mausol\u00e9e Sidi Brahim Riahi - \u0632\u0627\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u0633\u064a\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a photo2.jpg|thumb|Dome zaouia Sidi Brahim Riahi]]\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Tunisia-bio-stub}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riahi, Sidi Brahim}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people stubs]]\n", "text_old": "<br />{{Infobox person\n| name               = Brahim Riahi\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a\n| birth_name         = Abou Ishak Ibrahim Ben Abdelkader Riahi\n| birth_date         = 1766\n| birth_place        = [[Testour]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date         = August 7, 1850\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Tunisian\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Ibrahim Riahi,''' his birth name  '''Abou Ishak Ibrahim Ben Abdelkader Riahi'''  (1977  [[Testour]] \u2013 August 7, 1850)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.bnf.fr/fr/14651143/ibrahim_ibn__abd_al-qadir_al-_riyah_i/|title=Ibr\u0101h\u012bm ibn \u02bfAbd al-Q\u0101dir al- Riy\u0101\u1e25\u012b (1767-1850)|website=data.bnf.fr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>, was a [[Tunisia|Tunisian]] ambassador, theologian and  saint. A Sunni Muslim scholar, he is also a poet. He is the grandfather of [[Ali Riahi]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nIbrahim Riahi learned about the group of academics and lawyers from Tunisia, in particular: Hamza Al-Jibas, Saleh Al-Kawash, Muhammad Al-Fassi, Omar Bin Qassem Al-Mahjoub, Hassan Al-Sharif, Ahmed Bou Khurais, Ismail Al -Tamimi, Al-Taher Ben Massoud, and others.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a|date=2020-01-27|url=https://ar.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A5%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%8A%D9%85_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD%D9%8A&oldid=43176304|work=\u0648\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0628\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nSidi Brahim frequented from a young age a kouttab in [[Testour]] and showed talent for religious sciences and learning the [[Quran]]. Upon his arrival in [[Tunis]], around 1782, he studied at the Haouanet Achour madrassah and then at the Bir Lahjar madrassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080302042056/http://www.tunisia.strabon.org/amvppc/Tunis/Dossier%20Patrimoine/10zaouia_fr.html|title=Tourba et Zaouiya: Le mythe ...|date=2008-03-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAround 1790, he began teaching at Zitouna University where the future ministers Ibn Abi Dhiaf and B\u00e9ji Messaoudi as well as the greatest theologians of the time such as Mohamed Bayram IV and Mahmoud Kabadou were among his students.\n\nIn 1801, he was part of an embassy in [[Morocco]], where he stayed for several months, there he discovered the Sufi tariqa of the Tijaniyya and introduced it to Tunisia on his return.<ref>{{Citation|title=Sidi Brahim Riahi|date=2020-01-23|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Sidi_Brahim_Riahi&oldid=166662511|work=Wikip\u00e9dia|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum ==\nSidi Brahim is buried with some of his sons, sheikhs and theologians like him, in his mausoleum in the  Sidi Brahim Riahi street in the medina of Tunis named [[Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum]].\n[[File:Sidi Brahim Riahi Mausoleum - mausol\u00e9e Sidi Brahim Riahi - \u0632\u0627\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u0633\u064a\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a photo2.jpg|thumb|Dome zaouia Sidi Brahim Riahi]]\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Tunisia-bio-stub}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riahi, Sidi Brahim}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people stubs]]\n", "name_user": "Mccapra", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidi_Brahim_Riahi"}
